# Feature Planning — Reference

## Methodology: 5 Phases with Gates

| Phase | Name | What it does | Gate |
|-------|------|-------------|------|
| 1 | **Discovery** | Agent asks 10-20 business questions, searches existing patterns in codebase | User confirms all answered |
| 2 | **Business Refinement** | Documents rules in Given-When-Then per module. Marks `[NEEDS CLARIFICATION]` where uncertain | User approves business rules |
| 3 | **Technical Design** | Contract-First: API + schema BEFORE code. Mandatory reuse check | User approves contracts and schema |
| 4 | **Tasks** | Order: schema → API contracts → frontend → backend → integration. Each task traces to rule | User approves task list |
| 5 | **Implementation** | TDD per task (Red → Green). Contract vs actual reconciliation at end | Spec-validate |

**Principle**: Think outside-in (UI → contracts → routes → data), build inside-out (data → routes → contracts → UI).

## Classification

**SIMPLE** — ALL must be true:
1. Affects max 2 modules
2. Standard CRUD or extension of existing screen/endpoint
3. Does NOT introduce new domain concept
4. Has clear pattern in codebase to copy
5. Does NOT require integration with new external system
6. Does NOT have complex business rules

**COMPLEX** — Any criterion fails.

## Auto-Detection

```
User request
    ↓
Is it a new feature? (implement, create, add, new module)
    ├── NO → Implement directly (bug fix, refactoring, config)
    └── YES → Docs exist at {{paths.docsRoot}}/{{paths.rules}}/{module}/{{paths.businessRules}}/{feature}.md?
              ├── YES → Use {{paths.devPlans}}/{feature}.md as guide
              └── NO → BLOCK: invoke /plan-feature → docs → implement
```

## Scope per Role (Rule #5)

| Role | Scope | Cannot contain |
|------|-------|----------------|
| frontend/mobile | Layout, UX, visual states, mask validation | Domain calculations, business rules |
| backend | Validations, calculations, transformations, domain rules | UI logic, DDL |
| database | Schema DDL, migrations, indexes, constraints | Business logic, ORM with methods |
| agent-ai | Rules engine, pipelines, LLM, schedulers | API/frontend logic |
| e2e | BDD features, step definitions, page objects | Application code |

## Given-When-Then Format (Mandatory)

Every business rule MUST use this format:

```
Given {context/precondition}
When {user or system action}
Then {expected result}
```

**Example**:
```
Given a technician with 3 pending work orders
When the monitor clicks "Certify"
Then the system shows a confirmation modal with all 3 orders listed
And the "Confirm" button is enabled only if all orders are selected
```

Every rule MUST have at least 1 positive AND 1 negative scenario.

## Contract-First (Mandatory)

1. **Schema first**: Define tables/fields/migrations BEFORE business logic
2. **API contracts first**: Define endpoints, DTOs, response schemas BEFORE implementation
3. **Frontend after**: Components/screens are based on approved contracts

## Reuse Check (Mandatory)

Before creating ANY new endpoint or component:
1. `Grep` for similar patterns in existing codebase
2. If found → propose extension/reuse instead of creating new
3. Document reuse decision in the "Reuse" column of the dev plan

