## Validation Checklists

**business-rules**: Focused ONLY on this module | Rule IDs preserved | At least 1 positive + 1 negative | Given-When-Then on all rules | Data mapped | Self-contained (readable alone)

**test-plans**: Each rule has positive AND negative scenario | Consistent Gherkin format | Module-focused | Error scenarios included

**dev-plans**: Existing patterns mapped | Atomic and clear tasks | Reuse column filled | Local validation defined | Traced to rules

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| Implement without documenting | Skips business-rules | ALWAYS create business-rules first |
| Doc mixes layers | BFF rules in frontend doc | Each doc ONLY its module |
| Generic test cases | "Works correctly" | Use Given-When-Then with concrete values |
| Context overflow | Keep all inline | Save per module, use checkpoint |
| Ignore existing patterns | Don't explore before planning | Use Explore agents + Grep |
| Non-self-contained doc | References others without context | Each doc readable alone |
| Business logic in frontend | Don't validate scope | Frontends = visual. Logic → backend |
| Create API without checking existing | Don't search for reuse | Grep BEFORE creating endpoint/component |

## Tag [NEEDS CLARIFICATION]

When the agent is uncertain about a requirement, it MUST mark with `[NEEDS CLARIFICATION]` and move on. The user reviews and clarifies at the gate.

**Example**: `Given an offline technician [NEEDS CLARIFICATION: offline = no connection or unstable connection?]`

